Your current setup uses highly respected, industry-standard methods. However, as datasets grow from thousands of rows to tens of millions, there are key areas where we can make upgrades to dramatically improve speed and quality of detection.
Here is the evaluation of your current methods and recommended enhancements:
1. Near-Duplicate Detection (Fuzzy Matching)
Current Method: Pairwise fuzzy comparisons using rapidfuzz.
The Performance Issue: While rapidfuzz is implemented in C++ and is fast, doing a brute-force pairwise comparison has a complexity of $O(N^2)$. For a dataset with 50,000 rows, this requires 2.5 billion comparisons, which will hang or crash the worker process.
Recommended Upgrade: Introduce Locality-Sensitive Hashing (LSH) / MinHash.
What it does: Groups similar text records into "buckets" first. Only rows that share the same bucket are compared.
Speed Enhancement: Reduces complexity from $O(N^2)$ to nearly $O(N)$, allowing fuzzy deduplication on millions of rows in seconds.
2. Deep Data Quality Validation
Current Method: Great Expectations (GX) running in-memory on Pandas DataFrames.
The Performance Issue: GX is extremely feature-rich but carries heavy initialization and execution overhead. Loading millions of rows into Python memory to run GX validations will lead to OutOfMemory errors on standard servers.
Recommended Upgrade: Move to Pushdown Validation (Soda Core or GX SQL Sources).
What it does: Instead of loading dataframes into the Python memory space, these tools translate expectation rules into standard SQL queries (e.g. SELECT COUNT(*) FROM table WHERE email NOT LIKE '%@%') and execute them directly inside the Azure SQL database.
Speed & Scale Enhancement: Leverages the database engine's indexes and scaling. Computes checks on 10 million rows in milliseconds without consuming Python RAM.
3. Outlier Detection
Current Method: Isolation Forest (scikit-learn) in Python.
The Performance Issue: Excellent for multi-variable outlier detection, but requires fitting a machine learning model on CPU, which does not scale well on raw data servers.
Recommended Upgrade: Split into Hybrid Outlier Detection.
Simple Anomalies: Push univariate checks (like Z-score or standard deviation bounds) directly to the database via SQL.
Complex Anomalies: Sample the dataset using Stratified Sampling (sampling based on transaction size or category ratios) to train the Isolation Forest model on a smaller, high-leverage subset of data.
